#week-title("Two", "The Three Philosophical Principles")

=== Core Teaching

The entire art of alchemy proceeds from three principles. They are called Mercury,
Sulphur, and Salt — but these names refer not to the common substances of those
names, which are merely their lowest and most fixed expressions in the mineral
kingdom.

*Mercury* is the spirit-principle: the universal life force, the volatile, the
animating presence that makes a thing what it is. It is the same in all living
things, differing only in degree of refinement and in the kingdom through which
it expresses. In the vegetable kingdom it is found in the alcohol that rises from
fermentation; in the mineral kingdom it is the philosophic mercury of the metals.
Mercury is what rises when you heat a substance — the first thing to depart.

#doctrine[
  _"Mercury is the Soul of all Metals and Minerals. Without it, neither Sulphur
  nor Salt can exert any power or influence whatsoever. It is the Mover, the
  Universal Animator."_
  #align(right)[— _Golden Chain of Homer_, Part I, Ch. II (paraphrased)]
]

*Sulphur* is the soul-principle: the characterising force, the oily, aromatic,
combustible nature that gives each substance its individual identity and power.
This is why one plant differs from another even when the Mercury is the same.
In the laboratory, the Sulphur is found in the essential oils and the coloured
aromatic fraction — what rises slightly later than the pure Mercury, or separates
as a distinct layer.

*Salt* is the body-principle: the fixed, mineral residue that remains when everything
volatile has been driven off. It is the ash after the fire; the skeleton after the
flesh has gone. Contrary to what the materialist assumes, this is *not* dead matter
— it is the most fixed and crystallised expression of the plant's vital signature.
The Salt of each plant is unique. This is why two plants treated identically in the
laboratory will produce Salts of quite different character.

#doctrine[
  _"These three principles are not truly separate substances mixed together.
  They are three aspects or modes of a single reality in different degrees of
  coagulation and volatility. The volatile (Mercury) is the same substance as the
  fixed (Salt), seen at different points in the cycle of manifestation."_
  #align(right)[— GCH I, Part I; synthesised TTAO commentary]
]

*The Double Abyss.* The Golden Chain of Homer expresses the essential movement in
an alchemical verse that should be memorised early and returned to throughout the
curriculum:

#doctrine[
  _"The highest must become the lowest. \ The lowest again the Highest. \ The fixed
  must become quite volatile. \ Water and steam must be the earth."_
  #align(right)[— _Golden Chain of Homer_, Part I, the Double Abyss]
]

This is not poetry for decoration. It is a working description of the alchemical
process itself. In the laboratory: calcination drives the volatile out of the fixed,
leaving only the Salt (highest becomes lowest); cohobation returns the volatile to
the Salt, which absorbs and is elevated by it (lowest becomes highest again).

*One critical rule* must be established here and never forgotten: *the three
principles of one kingdom must not be mixed with those of another.* Vegetable Salt
must not be combined with animal Mercury. Mineral Salt must not be combined with
vegetable essence. Each kingdom operates at a distinct vibratory rate, and confusion
of kingdoms produces no alchemical result — only a confused mixture.

=== Topics This Week

- Mercury, Sulphur, and Salt: precise definitions in the alchemical sense
- Why common mercury, sulphur, and salt are not the alchemical equivalents
- The three principles as three modes of one substance, not three separate things
- The volatility spectrum: from pure Mercury (most volatile) through Sulphur to Salt (most fixed)
- How to identify the three principles in a plant: practical observation
- The three kingdoms and their distinct vibratory rates: why they must not be mixed
- The Golden Chain's Double Abyss: volatile and fixed as two poles of one reality

#inner-work[
  *The Threefold Breath*

  Add the colour-breath practice to the daily sitting. After the Third Eye Focus,
  settle and work with the three channels of the body:

  *Right side (Mercury / white):* Block the left nostril. Breathe in through the
  right, imagining the right side of the body filling with bright white vapour —
  clear, light, volatile. Breathe out white. Repeat three times.

  *Left side (Sulphur / red):* Block the right nostril. Breathe in through the left,
  imagining the left side filling with warm red vapour — the soul, the characterising
  fire. Breathe out red. Repeat three times.

  *Centre (Salt / blue):* Breathe freely through both nostrils, imagining a steady
  blue vapour filling the central axis of the body from crown to foot — the fixed,
  the stable, the crystallising. Breathe out blue. Repeat three times.

  Sit quietly with all three channels present simultaneously. This is not merely a
  visualisation exercise. The student is training perception of the same three
  principles within their own body that they are beginning to work with in the
  laboratory.

  *Numerology — Numbers 1 through 3 as Living Principles:*

  Begin a parallel study of numbers as living philosophical principles, not
  mathematical abstractions.

  - *1:* The pioneer, the undifferentiated creative impulse — Mercury as pure
    originating force. Nothing has yet been form; the one acts without
    resistance or differentiation.
  - *2:* The pair, volatile and fixed in their first tension — Sulphur as the
    second movement, the characterising separation. Two poles appear; they are
    drawn toward each other and repelled simultaneously.
  - *3:* The first stable triad — Mercury, Sulphur, Salt in their first coherent
    differentiation. The tension of the two resolves into a third that contains
    both. This is the foundation of all alchemical reasoning.

  Understanding numbers philosophically is the foundation for both Qabalah and
  the numerological dimension of alchemical work. The student should avoid
  _arithmetical_ thinking here — 1 + 2 = 3 is trivial. What matters is 1 _becoming_
  2, and 2 _resolving into_ 3.
]

